{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01BoSqY9mKT21m4AdjkxcJdb","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01RbfpQk9t9rUshq9aPo8oXZ","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cd /tmp/codeharness-verify-8-8-rust-documentation-scaffolding && claude --print --max-budget-usd 5 --allowedTools Bash Read Write Glob Grep Edit -p \"$(cat <<'PROMPT_EOF'\nYou are a black-box verifier. Your job is to verify that a software feature works correctly from the user's perspective — using ONLY the installed CLI, documentation, and observability data. You have NO access to source code.\n\n## Why Black-Box Verification\n\nThis workspace contains NO source code. The `src/` directory does not exist. This is intentional — you must verify the feature works as a user would experience it, not by reading implementation details. If you cannot verify a feature from docs + CLI alone, that is a REAL failure in the product's documentation or packaging.\n\n## Step 1: Read README.md\n\nStart by reading `README.md` in this workspace. It contains install and usage instructions for the project. Use it to understand how to exercise the CLI.\n\n## Step 2: Review Acceptance Criteria\n\nThe story file `story.md` contains the acceptance criteria you must verify. Read it now.\n\n## Step 3: Verify Each AC\n\nFor EACH acceptance criterion, you must:\n\n1. Run commands inside the Docker container via `docker exec codeharness-verify ...`\n2. Capture the command output as evidence\n3. Query observability endpoints if runtime evidence is needed\n\n### Docker Container\n\n- Container name: `codeharness-verify`\n- ALL CLI commands MUST run via: `docker exec codeharness-verify <command>`\n- Example: `docker exec codeharness-verify codeharness --version`\n\nThe container has the following tools installed:\n- `codeharness` — the project CLI\n- `claude` — Claude Code CLI\n- `curl`, `jq` — for querying observability endpoints\n- `node`, `npm` — Node.js runtime\n\n### Project Type: Node.js CLI\n\nExecute commands inside the container and capture stdout/stderr as evidence:\n- `docker exec codeharness-verify <cli-command> [args]`\n- Capture exit codes: `docker exec codeharness-verify sh -c '<command>; echo \"EXIT:$?\"'`\n- For Node.js projects, the built artifact is installed globally in the container.\n\n### Observability Endpoints\n\nQuery these from the HOST (not inside the container) for runtime evidence:\n\n- **VictoriaLogs** (logs): `http://localhost:9428`\n- **VictoriaMetrics** (metrics): `http://localhost:8428`\n- **VictoriaTraces** (traces): `http://localhost:16686`\n\n## Step 3.5: Observability Check After Each Command\n\nAfter EACH `docker exec` command you run, query the observability backend for log events from the last 30 seconds:\n\n```bash\ncurl 'http://localhost:9428/select/logsql/query?query=_stream_id:*&start=-30s&limit=100'\n```\n\n- If the response contains one or more log entries, the code path has observability coverage.\n- If the response contains zero log entries, include: `[OBSERVABILITY GAP] No log events detected for this user interaction`\n\n## Step 4: Write Proof Document\n\nWrite your verification proof to: `verification/8-8-rust-documentation-scaffolding-proof.md`\n\nUse this format for each AC:\n\n```text\n## AC N: <description>\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify <command>\n```\n\n```output\n<actual output>\n```\n```\n\n**IMPORTANT: Only use `bash` and `output` as code fence languages.** Never use bare ``` fences without a language tag.\n\n## Critical Rules\n\n1. **ALL commands MUST use `docker exec codeharness-verify ...`** — do NOT run commands directly on the host filesystem.\n2. **Do NOT attempt to access source code** — there is no `src/` directory in this workspace.\n3. **Report REAL failures** — if a feature does not work, report that as a verification failure. Do NOT fabricate passing evidence.\n4. **Every AC needs functional evidence** — reading docs alone is not evidence. You must execute commands and capture output.\n5. **[ESCALATE] is ONLY for things that are genuinely impossible to automate** — physical hardware, paid external services, human visual judgment. Infrastructure problems are NOT valid escalation reasons.\n6. **Never switch to unit-testable verification.** If Docker verification does not work, report WHY as a [FAIL].\n\n## Verification Strategy for This Story\n\nThis story is about Rust documentation scaffolding — specifically:\n- AC1-3: Functions that return Rust-specific labels, coverage tool names, and AGENTS.md content\n- AC4-6: `getProjectName()` reading from Cargo.toml  \n- AC7: Zero regression in tests\n\nTo verify AC1-6, you need to exercise `codeharness init` on a Rust project inside the container. Create a temp directory with a Cargo.toml file and run `codeharness init --json` to see if it detects Rust correctly and generates proper documentation.\n\nFor AC4-6 specifically, create different Cargo.toml configurations:\n- AC4: Cargo.toml with [package] name and NO package.json → project name should come from Cargo.toml\n- AC5: Both Cargo.toml and package.json → project name should come from package.json\n- AC6: Cargo.toml with name only in [dependencies] → should fall back to directory basename\n\nFor AC7, run `docker exec codeharness-verify sh -c 'cd /opt/codeharness && npm test 2>&1'` to verify tests pass (the source + tests are at /opt/codeharness in the container).\n\nIMPORTANT: The container has the full project at /opt/codeharness with node_modules. You can run tests there.\nPROMPT_EOF\n)\" 2>&1","description":"Run black-box verifier session","timeout":300000},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":255,"cache_read_input_tokens":55506,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":255},"output_tokens":64,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_